<paragraph id="E97036DD3F1BFF8CFF76F9F7FDECF96A" blockId="46.[151,1437,1649,2036]" box="[151,524,1649,1676]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
Size. Reaches 
<quantity id="2E379B383F1BFF8CFEDBF9F7FE9FF96D" box="[314,383,1649,1676]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" unit="cm" value="13.0">13 cm</quantity>
total length.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A1D565563F1BFF8DFF26F913FCEFFE68" lastPageId="47" lastPageNumber="48" pageId="46" pageNumber="47" type="description">
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F1BFF8CFF26F913FD7AF882" blockId="46.[151,1437,1649,2036]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
Morphology. D VI + I,10; A I,9; P 17. Body moderately elongate, the depth about 5 times in standard length. Head subcylindrical, snout short and blunt. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F1BFF8CFD60F93FFB97F932" bold="true" box="[641,1143,1721,1747]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Eyes elevated above dorsal profile of head</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F1BFF8CFB67F93FFB2BF932" box="[1158,1227,1721,1747]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1117,1141]" captionTargetBox="[151,1437,181,1093]" captionTargetId="figure-19@14.[151,1437,181,1093]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 3. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Cryptocentrus caeruleopunctatus. Photo by S.V. Bogorodsky, Lahami Bay, Egypt, Red Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601571" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601571/files/figure.png" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Caudal peduncle deep, but lower than body depth. Spines of first dorsal fin not elongate. 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F1BFF8CFC2FF95BFA7CF916" bold="true" box="[974,1436,1757,1783]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Second dorsal fin higher than the first</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F1BFF8CFF41F887FF03F8FA" box="[160,227,1793,1819]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1117,1141]" captionTargetBox="[151,1437,181,1093]" captionTargetId="figure-19@14.[151,1437,181,1093]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 3. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Cryptocentrus caeruleopunctatus. Photo by S.V. Bogorodsky, Lahami Bay, Egypt, Red Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601571" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601571/files/figure.png" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Pelvic fins joined medially, reaching anus. Caudal fin rounded, its length about equal to head length (
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F1BFF8CFAB5F887FF33F8DE" author="Goren, M." pageId="46" pageNumber="47" pagination="13 - 64" refId="ref55441" refString="Goren, M. (1979) The Gobiinae of the Red Sea (Pisces: Gobiidae). Senckenbergiana Biologica, 60 (1 / 2), 13 - 64." type="journal article" year="1979">Goren 1979</bibRefCitation>
). Body covered with scales; no scales on head, prepelvic area, and pectoral-fin base, but scales poorly or not visible on live specimen photographs (
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F1BFF8CFDA6F8CFFD6CF882" box="[583,652,1865,1891]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1117,1141]" captionTargetBox="[151,1437,181,1093]" captionTargetId="figure-19@14.[151,1437,181,1093]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 3. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Cryptocentrus caeruleopunctatus. Photo by S.V. Bogorodsky, Lahami Bay, Egypt, Red Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601571" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601571/files/figure.png" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F1BFF8CFF26F8EBFA7CF812" blockId="46.[151,1437,1649,2036]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">
Live coloration. Grayish brown, grading posteriorly to dark olive-brown with 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F1BFF8CFBBAF8EBFC8EF84A" bold="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">deep red blue-edged spots subequal to pupil size on head, anterior body, and dorsal fins</emphasis>
; 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F1BFF8CFC9DF817FDAFF82E" bold="true" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">dorsal half of body with 2 dark spots of about eye size, circled with blue-green dots,</emphasis>
one under middle of first dorsal fin and one below fourth or fifth dorsal-fin soft ray; 
<emphasis id="DBBBEACF3F1BFF8CFF18F85FFBE8F812" bold="true" box="[249,1032,2009,2035]" pageId="46" pageNumber="47">a series of 7 oblique pale lines with blue dots on mid and rear body</emphasis>
; head with an irregular dark red bar,
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F1AFF8DFF76FF11FC50FF34" blockId="47.[151,1437,151,393]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
edged with blue-green, extending ventrally from eye (
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F1AFF8DFD16FF11FCDCFF50" box="[759,828,151,177]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1117,1141]" captionTargetBox="[151,1437,181,1093]" captionTargetId="figure-19@14.[151,1437,181,1093]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 3. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Cryptocentrus caeruleopunctatus. Photo by S.V. Bogorodsky, Lahami Bay, Egypt, Red Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601571" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601571/files/figure.png" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). The anal and paired fins olivaceous, with small pale yellowish spots, those on anal fin mainly in 2 rows along base (
<figureCitation id="71F42A583F1AFF8DFCBFFF3DFC42FF34" box="[862,930,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1117,1141]" captionTargetBox="[151,1437,181,1093]" captionTargetId="figure-19@14.[151,1437,181,1093]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 3. Live coloration in its natural habitat of Cryptocentrus caeruleopunctatus. Photo by S.V. Bogorodsky, Lahami Bay, Egypt, Red Sea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6601571" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6601571/files/figure.png" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F1AFF8DFF26FF59FCA6FF18" blockId="47.[151,1437,151,393]" box="[199,838,223,249]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Similar species. No similar species in the Mediterranean.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F1AFF8DFF26FE85FBEBFEA1" blockId="47.[151,1437,151,393]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
Habitat. Silty to coarse sand bottom, generally adjacent to sheltered reefs or seagrass beds, but also in calm seaward areas from depths of 
<quantity id="2E379B383F1AFF8DFE07FEA1FDDEFEA0" box="[486,574,295,321]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" metricValueMax="2.4" metricValueMin="0.2" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" unit="m" value="13.0" valueMax="24.0" valueMin="2.0">
2– 
<specimenCount id="FFC9FD543F1AFF8DFDE3FEA1FDDEFEA0" box="[514,574,295,321]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" type="generic">24 m</specimenCount>
</quantity>
. Shares a burrow with snapping shrimps.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E97036DD3F1AFF8DFF26FECDFCEFFE68" blockId="47.[151,1437,151,393]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
Geographic distribution. Restricted to the Red Sea and Gulf of 
<collectingRegion id="2B0BF83F3F1AFF8DFC77FECDFC1CFE84" box="[918,1020,331,357]" country="Djibouti" name="Tadjourah" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Tadjoura</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="91D8764D3F1AFF8DFBE9FECDFB89FE84" box="[1032,1129,331,357]" name="Djibouti" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Djibouti</collectingCountry>
. Reported from the eastern Mediterranean coast of 
<collectingCountry id="91D8764D3F1AFF8DFE41FEE9FE3EFE68" box="[416,478,367,393]" name="Israel" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Israel</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="8D5E4B2C3F1AFF8DFE0CFEE9FCE3FE68" author="Rothman, S. B. S. &amp; Goren, M." box="[493,771,366,393]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" pagination="1 - 2" refId="ref63931" refString="Rothman, S. B. S. &amp; Goren, M. (2015) First record of the Red Sea shrimp-goby Cryptocentrus caeruleopunctatus in the Mediterranean Sea. Marine Biodiversity Records, 8 (e 157), 1 - 2. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 1755267215001323" type="journal article" year="2015">Rothman &amp; Goren 2015</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
